Briefly describe the types of shock giving clinical features of each(5 marks)
1.HYPOVOLAEMIC SHOCK:

Occurs from inadequate blood volume due to hemorrhage., trauma, burns or dehydration from diarrhea, vomiting leading to decrease in cardiac output and decreased tissue perfusion.

\section*{CLINICAL FEATURES}
-Pale and cool skin
-Increases heart rate
-Oliguria
-Hypotension,
-Tachypnea,
- Restlessness due to hypoperfusion,
- Cold extremities,
- Altered mental status,
- Decreased pulse pressure

\section*{2.CARDIOGENIC SHOCK:}

This is acute circulatory failure with sudden with sudden fall in cardiac output from acute disease of the heart without actual reduction in blood volume.

\section*{CLINICAL FEATURES}

Shortness of breath, Hypotension, Tachycardia, Tachypnea, Oliguria ,Distended neck veins, Lower limb oedema, Basal crepitation, Raised JVP

\section*{3.DISTRIBUTIVE SHOCK :}

Occurs due to abnormal distribution of blood flow .This type is further divided into three subtypes .They include :

✓ SEPTIC SHOCK:
It is induced by severe bacterial infections or septicemia. It may result from either gram negative or gram positive bacteria which release toxins which results to activation of macrophages and monocytes and vasodilation leading to hypotension and decrease in tissue perfusion.

\section*{CLINICAL FEATURES}

Fever, Hypothermia, Rapid heart rate, Warm or cold skin, Altered mental status, Hypotension, Oliguria

✓ NEUROGENIC SHOCK:
Results from a high spinal cord injury resulting to loss of sympathetic tone leading to Vasodilation hence decrease in venous return.

\section*{CLINICAL FEATURES}

Hypotension, Bradycardia, Warm, dry skin
✓ ANAPHYLACTIC SHOCK:
Results from an antigen - antibody reaction that rapidly occurs after an antigen to which the person is sensitive to enters into the circulation leading to peripheral vasodilation,increased capillary permeability,decrease in cardiac output and decrease In atrial pressure leading to hypoperfusion.

\section*{CLINICAL FEATURES}

Difficulty in breathing, swelling, Itching, Rapid pulse, Hypotension, Hives.

\section*{4:OBSTRUCTIVE SHOCK;}

Occurs due to physical obstruction of blood flow i. e Obstruction of venous return and circulatory obstruction eg in Constructive pericarditis Cardiac tamponade, Tension pneumothorax and Pulmonary embolism. This leads to reduced blood to the lungs hence resulting into decreased cardiac output and hypotension

\section*{CLINICAL FEATURES}

Low BP, Distended neck veins. Difficult in breathing. Tracheal deviation, Muffled heart sounds

